You have tested everything yourselves
Ramesh said patiently
You have cleverly hidden something in the box
That would be clear now, the officer said, cutting the bottom of the box with a knife
Ramesh's body trembled
The whole body became wet with sweat
"Ranrudha cheated on me," he told himself
There was a hidden place at the bottom of the box
There were plastic bags filled with some white powder
Heroin, the officer said in surprise
Theft We will arrest you for bringing prohibited items into our country
said the officer in a stern voice
I'm sorry I don't know anything
Someone I know sent this fraudulently
He had told me that there were only clothes
So I brought this box, Ramesh said sadly
I don't seem to have the right to show mercy or spare anything in this matter
You have committed a terrible crime
So saying that you can say what you have to say in court tomorrow
The officer gave orders to the soldiers
They handcuffed Ramesh and took him to prison
Even Ramesh's prayers in court the next day were in vain
The judge addressed him and showed him the name and address of the prisoner of war
"If he is caught and your statement is untrue, the punishment would be reduced," he said
Ramesh had nothing like that
Ranrudha had sent a picture of Ramesh to his relative
He had said that my relative would come and welcome you himself
That is why he had not given a picture of the bond or a name
So unable to say anything Ramesh remained silent
Then the judge found Ramesh guilty
Five years imprisonment was prescribed as punishment
Fascinated, Ramesh is currently spending his days in prison in an unfamiliar country, experiencing a harsh sentence
When will I be freed and how can I go back to my country even after I am freed?
How can I show my face to my parents and friends even if I go there
He spends his days crying that he is lost and deceived
The ungrateful Brahmin
Author: Hirendra Kumar Sharma
There used to be a Brahmin named Gautama
Very wicked by nature he made a living begging
He also committed sinful acts
Once a religious scholar came to that city
He saw Gautama and enlightened him to give up sinful deeds
Gautama was impressed by his advice and started his journey thinking of a way to get money
During the journey he got lost in the forest
Wandering about there he entered a garden
There lived a swan named Rajadharma, the son of Maharshi Kasyapa
Gautama sat down under a tree in exhaustion
That was the tree where the swan lived
In the evening the swan returned to his abode and saw Gautama sitting there
Devoted to hospitality, he introduced himself and treated him with fruits and other things
I also made a soft bed with flowers for him to lie on
He spoke fondly to Gautama who was lying there, beating him with his white wings
He also asked why he had come here
Gautama described his poverty and said that he was trying to get money
Rajadharma wanted to help him
He said to Gautama Three yojanas away from here lives my friend the king of demons
You go there
That he would help
In the morning Gautama set out from there and came to the king of the demons
The king of the demons, however, knowing that he had been sent by his friend Rajadharma, received him with joy
He also gave him a lot of money
The next morning Gautama left there and came to the same forest where Rajadharma was
Very satisfied to see him, Rajadharma still entertained him
He gave me good food
After dinner he lit a fire to protect it from wild animals
I also arranged for him to lie down in a suitable place
He himself lay down next to him
In the middle of the night Gautama fell asleep
Then an evil thought occurred to him
He thought my house was too far from here
I have accepted a lot of money from the king of demons out of greed
His weight is great
You may not even find anything to eat in the middle of the road
So I'm going to kill this fat swan and take it away
That will avoid food problems along the way
Thinking thus the cruel Brahmin killed the innocent swan lying beside him
He cooked his meat in the fire and took the money and left
Meanwhile, the demon king Virupaksha was also worried about his friend
He said to his son, 'Son, my best friend Rajadharma used to come here every day
But he hasn't come in two days
I feel worried
Even the characteristics of that Brahmin were not auspicious
So you go and see how my friend is doing
At his father's command the prince went with the other demons to the residence of Rajadharma
But he found only the bones of Raja Dharma there
Angrily he started searching for Gautama
Not long afterwards the demons saw Gautama not far away
They bound him and brought him to the demon king
They told him everything that had happened
The demon king fainted on hearing the news of the death of his friend Rajadharma
After a while he woke up in anger
Bhoh told the demons to kill this ungrateful Brahmin and eat his flesh
But the demons, O king, we do not wish to eat this sinful soul
Because if we eat the flesh of this ungrateful man, we too will be sinners
There is atonement for all sins in this world
But no atonement for betrayal
So we said we were sorry
Then the king of demons cut Gautama's body into pieces and gave it to other creatures
But even animals, birds and insects have not eaten the flesh of the ungrateful man
Then the king of demons arranged for the funeral of Rajadharma
He made a sandalwood coffin and placed the bones on top of it
At the same time the cow of desire was flying in the sky with Indra
Some drops of nectar fell from her mouth onto it
That kept the royal religion alive
The demon king was very happy to see his friend alive and hugged him lovingly
A story quoted from the Mahabharata
An accomplished judge
Author: Kaulgi Sheshacharya
There was a judge in a certain city
He was known to be very skilled in the administration of justice
The king of that kingdom heard the news
and wanted to test that judge
For that the king disguised himself and traded like a merchant
His judge left for the city
On the way he saw a monk
That monk was begging
He also came to the merchant and asked for alms
Then the king, dressed as a merchant, gave him a coin and set out
Suddenly the monk himself, the merchant, mounted his horse
He asked me to take him to the trade fair too
That trade fair, however, was held in the city of this judge
The king sent his horse to the city and told the monk to get off his horse
Then the monk said, 'This horse is mine
You said you should get off
An argument broke out between the two
Even after going, no avoidance was found
Then the king went before the magistrates and told them everything that had happened
The judge called the guards and ordered them to bring the monk here with his horse
When the monk came with the horse, the judge said, "Let this horse be here today
Both should come to court tomorrow
Then he said he would give the verdict and sent them away
Meanwhile, the judge merchants brought many horses that looked like horses
placed in the court yard
The next day both came to court
The judge first called the monk and ordered him to identify which of these horses was yours
The monk pointed to the horse
Now the judge called the merchant apart and ordered him to identify the horse as well
He also showed the same horse
The judge then ruled that the horse belonged to the merchant and not to the beggar
The disappointed monk left in shame
Then the king asked the judge, telling him his true identity
How did you decide that the horse was mine?
The judge said as I took the monk to the horse
Then the horse showed contempt for him
But when he took you, the horse showed you affection
So it was only after seeing the behavior of the horse that I decided that the horse was yours
The Maharaja was further satisfied with the words of the judge
The shape of the geography
The author is Raghav from Hariharpur
Once the teacher asked while teaching geography
The inspector will arrive tomorrow
If he asks what the shape of the earth is, what answer should he give?
No student answered
Then the teacher said angrily if you remain silent
The pride of our school is disappearing
This is the shape of the geography
"Remember everyone," he said, pointing to his destroyer
That destructive pot was spherical
The next day the inspector came to the school
He asked a student what the shape of the globe was
Then the student stood up and said
Mr. Geography was spherical
That's what makes four weapons today
The teacher had brought a spherical destroyer the day before
That day, however, his destructive pot was square
So the student had answered that way
Time is stronger
Author Addepalli Rajeshwari
Once Vishnu came to Kailas to see Lord Shiva for some work
Garuda, the vehicle of Vishnu, had also come with him
Vishnu and Shankara were having a conversation
The unemployed eagle left there thinking that he was coming back after a visit to Kailas
While wandering around the eagle saw a wonderful sight
A herd of more than a thousand snakes was stuck here and there on Kailas
All those snakes ignored the eagle and stuck around fearlessly
They even roamed around the eagle
Unable to tolerate the behavior of the snakes the eagle ran after them
Then all the snakes entered the body of Shiva
They stood like sashes and ornaments on the matted hair of Shiva around his neck and chest
Seeing the fearlessness of the snakes and the pale face of the eagle even in the presence of the eagle, Vishnu called out to the eagle
Placing her hand on his back, comforting him
Don't think, my child, that snakes are stronger than you or that you are weak
This is Kailas
It is the abode of Lord Shankara, the god of gods
Therefore, the disrespect of snakes is justified
Because the power of snakes is now in Shankara in the hands of Pinaka
So you are unable to end your enmity with the snakes
Now the time is stronger for the snakes themselves, he said
Then hearing the words of goodness of Vishnu
Garuda left the snake hunt and went out to see Kailas
The story within the Vishnu Purana
Oh, the devotion of the scholar
Author Shobhna
In a certain village there lived a scholar named Krishna Sharma
He had great knowledge of all four Vedas
Many people came to Krishna Sharma's house to learn
There was a river flowing in that village
On the other side of the river lived a milkman
Every day she brought milk to Krishna Sharma's house and gave it to him
Once she became ill
So she sent her daughter to sell the milk
From then on, it was the daughter who did the work
But the girl brought milk late every day
This caused Krishna Sharma to have to do all his work late in the morning
Angry with him he called the girl one day
Your mother would bring milk quickly and give it to you
I asked why you were late
The girl was afraid when she heard the words of the wise man
O great soul I must come back after crossing the river
But she said she was afraid to come in the morning
Then let the wise man go with patience or fear
God is everywhere, indeed
He ordered her to come early in the morning, remembering the name of Lord Rama, the all-pervading
The next day, before the Pandit got up, the girl had brought the milk and set it down
Krishna Sharma looked at the girl in surprise as she smiled softly
Then, O venerable one, as per your words, she came swimming in the river, remembering the name of Rama
Lord Rama came with me like a protector
She said she was not afraid at all
The scholar looked at her suspiciously
Have you become confused?
Sri Rama never comes
Even so he laughed saying that he should not come with an ignorant girl like you
Then that girl then come with me
You see what happens, said the scholar
She took him with her to the riverbank
The water flow in the river was flowing at great speed
But with a pure mind the girl started swimming in the river remembering the name of Rama
She stood in the middle of the river and called the scholar
Astonished, the learned man set foot in the river, remembering the name of Rama
And went a little farther
Meanwhile, a gust of wind began to blow in the river
Then the wise man said in fear O lord protect me Is there anyone on the bank of the river
He stopped remembering the name of Rama and cried out loudly
Then the girl, sir, don't be afraid
"Come here to chant the name of Rama," she said in a calm voice
But the scholar did not listen to her
Screaming, he sank into the water
The scholar's hands were visible only on the water
The sound of Rama Rama could be heard from the shore
Non-violation of command
Author: Chandrashekhar
There was a judge in a certain village
Everyone in the village was afraid of him
It was a rule that no one should leave the village in violation of his orders
In the same village there were two lovers named Rama and Bhima
Rama was making a pot
Bhima was building a hearse
Both were philanthropists
Once Bhima came to the city without the permission of the judge
At the same time an elderly woman passed away in the house of the relative of the judge
There was no Bhima to build the coffin then
So the angry judge called Bhima the next day and threatened him
He ordered me not to go anywhere without my permission
The other day for some reason Rama and Bhima had to go to the city
So they went to his house to get permission from the judge
But the judge had gone to town to get medicine for his mother
Unable to disobey the orders of the judges they were very worried
After all, no one should be in trouble even in our absence
Having said this, the judge placed two coffins and two clay pots in front of the house
They set out for the city
If anyone needs these, let him use them
Thinking about this they both left calmly
Meanwhile, the judge who had gone to the city came to the village with the doctor
He shivered at the sight of the people and the two hearses in front of the house
The doctor left saying that I was late for my arrival
Hearing the noise of people outside, the judge's wife and mother opened the door and saw it
The judge was surprised to see them and then learned the real situation
He condemned his own indiscretion in many ways
He who has not served Mukunda for a moment
Author: Dr. Haripal Dwivedi
Maharshi Shuka was a great ascetic
He practiced austerities, detached from worldly things
Rambha, the nymph of the heavenly world, wanted to break the austerities of the great sage Shuka
So she came to him and tried hard to attract him with her luxurious meetings
But even seeing her unique beauty, the parrot was not disturbed
Rambha followed the effort again
Then Shukdev asked her
"O goddess why are you trying to attract my attention
Rambha said I want to make you drink such juice
That you’ve never done it in your life
Shukdev said, "O Goddess
I am drinking some wonderful juice every moment
If I am deprived of that taste even for a moment, life itself is useless
That is, the life of a man who has not served Mukunda for a moment has been wasted
If a man remains even for a moment without serving the Lord
Then his life itself becomes meaningless
Therefore, O Goddess, I have forsaken for a moment the drinking of the taste in the form of serving the feet of Mukunda
I don't want to waste my life
What about me with other things besides that
However, Rambha was not disappointed
She began to describe her beauty again
She said that woman was also created by God
Therefore, women should not be ignored
And something else you don't know
A woman's body is full of such fragrance
That if one does not feel that pleasure
Then his life itself is in vain
Then Shukadeva spoke politely
O Goddess by your grace I have learned for the first time that a woman's body is so fragrant
May it be if I am born again as a human being by the inspiration of the Lord
So all I want is to live for nine months in the womb of a worshipful mother like you and experience that happiness
But now I have to serve the Lord
That you should forgive me
The supremely wise Shukadeva did not even condemn the female body
He did not even deviate from his loyalty
Surprised by this, Rambha abandoned her effort and returned
A king without discrimination
Author: Chandrashekhar
In a certain kingdom there was a king who ruled
That Maharaja was good by nature
Although he was good, he always acted without thinking when he was working
His ministers were the same
Once the forest dwellers living in the forest next to his kingdom came to the royal assembly
Their leader prayed to the Maharaja
Maharaja there is a great disturbance of tigers in our forest area these days
Please protect us from the tigers
The king thought for a moment after hearing the words of the forest dwellers
Then he said you stay calm
I will make appropriate arrangements to prevent tiger suffering
Then he called the craftsmen
and wrote a stone rule through it
It was written on that stone rule that
Tigers are prohibited from entering this area
Therefore tigers should not roam here anymore
All the tigers should go to another forest
Then, at the command of the Maharaja, the royal servants took the stone throne
They placed it in the forest where tigers roam most
The king was also very satisfied that I had taken good measures to prevent the suffering of the tigers
Like the king and the people, the forest dwellers began to move about there without fear
Gradually they all became food for the tigers
Everything is lucky
Author: Narasimha Bhatta
In a certain village there lived a farmer with his son
Once the farmer sowed seeds in his field
The rainfall was also good that year
The atmosphere was also very appropriate
Then one day the farmer went to the field with his son
The son looked at the field and said to his father
Dad, the rain is right this year
The seed soaking has also been done on time
Therefore, there will be more grain available this year
Then the father said, "My son, everything is up to fate
A few days passed
The seeds were all sprouted
Seeing that, the son said
Dad that almost all the seeds have sprouted
Then the father said again that everything was due to fate
Two months have passed again
All the seedlings became crops
Flowers and grain grew
Then the son and the father will now have abundant grain
That we can eat safely all year round
Even then, my father's answer was that it was all luck
In time when the grain is ripe
Then they harvested the grain and separated the crops and brought them home
He mixed the grain and prepared the food
Everyone in the farmer's house was sitting down to eat
Then the son said to his father, "Father, look at the fruit of our labor before us
Even then, the father said it was all about luck
Having heard this word from my father many times
The son became angry and kicked the food on the plate
I got up from there without eating
After the anger subsided, he knew that his father's words were true
Because nothing happens without God's will
Not one of the plates of food spread out in front of him was edible
Then the words came out of his mouth that everything was due to fate
Self-awareness
The author is Vivekananda
In a certain village a mother lived with her son with difficulty
The mother had great love for her son
Once the son was sitting at the door of the house
At that time a man was walking down the road
As he hurried away a wallet fell from his treasury
But he couldn't know it
Then he went on with speed
The boy who was sitting there quickly got up and accepted the wallet and gave it to his mother
The mother said to her son with satisfaction
Son, let him earn money from here
Hearing his mother's words made a great impression on him
The boy left all his work every day and began to sit at the door
The days have passed
But he got nothing
Then he thought there was no point in it
Money does not always fall from anyone's coffers
So I have to drop it myself
Then he went to the crowd and started stealing
Every day he gave the money he had stolen to his mother
The mother was also satisfied
In time the boy grew up
He thought there was no point in this petty theft
I should rob a rich man's house
Then you get a lot of money
So he went to the city
And there, at midnight, he entered the house of a certain rich man
By then the landlord had woken up
He made a noise
The household also woke up
All together they arrested him and took him to the police station
The guards put him in jail
He was sentenced to two years in prison as punishment in court
Hearing the news of his son his mother came to the court to meet him
She had brought food to give to her son
She was saddened to see her son's condition
She took a bowl of food to feed her son and placed it in his mouth
Then the son suddenly bit her hand with his teeth
Then he addressed his mother sadly
Mom, the first time I brought the wallet and gave it to you
Then if you had given me a slap instead of affection
Then I would not have been in such a bad situation today
It is because of your greater affection
That I am now experiencing imprisonment
The mother became self-conscious when she heard her son's words
She said to her son in tears
Calf, your words have removed my ignorance
My confusion also disappeared
I'm sorry
I look forward to the time when your prison stay is over
You finished the punishment and became a gentleman
That it is my pleasure that he will come home
The wisdom of the guardian of the righteous
Author: P. K. Narayanan Nambyar
In a certain kingdom there was a king named Dharmapala
He was once traveling in the kingdom
As he was walking he saw two old men arguing with each other in the middle of the road
They had the same appearance
Astonished at the sight he ordered the soldiers to bring them to him
The soldiers went and brought them back
The Maharaja asked a question addressing them
Why is there such a quarrel between you two?
Then one of them said
O great king I am a Brahmin named Agni Sharma
From a distant city I was walking this road to my village with my wife and sons
We stayed for a while to see the lake here
My wife went to the lake with her son to drink water
Then this man came from somewhere
He says that I am Agni Sharma
That this is my wife
That's why the quarrel started
Then the Maharaja remembered the specialty of that place
There lives a Brahma Rakshasa
That he is cheating on everyone
So he decided that
It is the Brahma Rakshasa who has come in the guise of a Brahmin
So one of these two is a real Brahmin
Another is a Brahmin in hypocritical disguise
Somehow it should be known which of them is the real Brahmin
So he called the son of the Brahmin and suggested that he should tell him which of these two was his father
The boy saw them again and again
But they were the same in colour, form, shape and so on
There was not the slightest difference between them
So the boy could not recognize who his father was between them
Then the Maharaja summoned the wife of the Brahmin to him
and asked her in secret that
Does your husband have any distinctive identification on his body?
Then she said he had a tiny crest on his head
Then the king summoned the two old men to him
I removed both of them simultaneously
Then he saw a fine crest on the head of one of them
The other had no crest on his head
So the Maharaja knew which of them was the real Agni Sharma
Yet the Maharaja stood as if he knew nothing
And then he thought of a way to stop the Brahma-rakshasa
So he ordered soldiers to bring a big box there
Then the two old men said I am doing a test
Then you will know who the real Agni Sharma is
What is the test, they asked
Let each of you enter this box and come out
That is the test
Both agreed
First the crested old man entered the box and came out
Then when the second old man entered the box
Then the king immediately locked her door
He also nailed to the rhythm
Then, at his command, the servants threw the box into the river
Thus the Maharaja by a means stopped the Brahma-rakshasa and removed the trouble of Agni Sharma
Agni Sharma also went to his village with his wife and sons, repeatedly praising the wisdom of the Maharaja
The fruit of deceit
The author is Sadhu Vishwavallabhadas
In a certain forest lived many kinds of animals
The king of all of them was a lion
Once the lion was afflicted with some disease
All the creatures learned about his illness and came to see him
But a fox didn't come
To see yourself suffering from disease
The lion did not know whether all the animals had come or not
Then a camel spoke to the lion
O great king all the creatures came to see you when they learned of your illness
But the arrogant fox did not come
The lion became very angry when he heard this
The next day the fox learned through others that
That the camel has been lying to me in front of the lion
So he hurried to see the lion
and bowed down to him with devotion from afar
Seeing the fox the lion became angry and shouted loudly
Ray roared, "You fool, why haven't you come to see me so far?"
The fox said, acting polite
I am sorry, sir
I'm just coming back after learning of your ill health and taking his medicine
Thinking about this I went to the doctor
So that I was late in coming
The satisfied lion in a calm voice
I asked if the doctor had given me any medicine
The fox said, "O great king, the doctor did not give any medicine
But he has mentioned the course of treatment
If you drink the blood of a camel, the disease will surely subside soon
The lion called out to the camel
The camel came with devotion
The lion jumped on him and killed him and drank his blood
Because of his cruelty the camel died on its own
Equal priority
Author Shanta Muralidhar Kulkarni
Two friends lived in a certain village
One of them was a lucky man
The other is a karmavadi
The lucky man thought that everything happened because of fate
If the pace of destiny is good, abundant wealth can be obtained even without effort
But the thinking of the Karmaists was quite different
His entire faith is in action
He meant that everything bears fruit only through effort
Sometimes an argument broke out between them
Even after a long dispute when no decision has been reached
Then they went to the Maharaja
Sir, you yourself tell the decision
They told him whether fate was better or action
The king arrested them both and sent them to prison
And he said you will be in prison for three days
In the meantime, the debate will be decided on its own
There was no provision for them to eat or drink in the prison
They were both weak from hunger and thirst
On the third day at night the Maharaja entered the prison by a secret passage
He placed a vessel filled with emulsion there
It was dark in the prison
The fragrance of payasam spread everywhere
Then the diligent thought this is my testing time
There is payasam somewhere nearby
If I try, I can get that payasam
Thinking thus, he moved his hands and feet with great effort and approached the payasam pot
and began to eat the payasam
Then a piece of stone stuck in his face
He thought with this piece of stone I would beat the lucky man
And I say my stomach is full of effort
In the meantime, the fortune teller thinks
This is my testing time
There is payasam somewhere nearby
If that’s my luck, I definitely get it
But I will not make an effort for that
At that moment a piece of stone falls on him
Then that this piece of stone would be my destiny
This is the only way to get my job done
Thinking so he kept him near him
Then he found more than ten pieces of stone in the same order
He saved everyone, too
In the morning the prison door opens
The Maharaja, the ministers and other people come there
They all see that the diligent is saturated with eating payasam
Everyone greets him with cheers
But when they see the fortuneteller
But then they are surprised
Because he had more than ten precious gems in front of him
He thought they were a rock at night and kept them
Everyone greeted him with cheers
Everyone is wondering what kind of decision the Maharaja is making now
Then the Maharaja said
Oh people, the argument between these two is pointless
Because without effort, destiny does not bear fruit
Without fate, even fruit is not accomplished
Therefore, they have equal priority
The suffering of others is one's own suffering
Author Vijayalakshmi Saraswati
In a certain village lived an old woman
She has only one son
Mother and son are very kind
Their house was very small
Sometimes the old woman became ill
She wanted the bark of the lodhra tree for making medicine
So she told her son
Son, there is a lodhra tree in the forest
You go there and get some skin
The son took the ax and went to the forest
I saw the lodhra tree
He skinned it with an ax and brought it home
The old woman accepted it and prepared the medicine
She also became healthy by taking it
Once again the mother saw her son's white clothes dyed red
In terror she asked her son
Calf, how bloody are your white clothes
What happened to it?
The son said nothing
Mother asked pleadingly again
Tell me what happened, calf
Then the son said
Mom that day you told me to bring the bark of the lodhra tree
While cutting down that tree, the thought occurred to me that
How much pain the tree must have felt when the bark was removed
Although the tree cannot speak, it must be in pain
Today I decided that I should find out what kind of pain the tree must have felt at that time
That's why I removed some skin from my body myself
Then there is blood flow
That's why my white clothes are stained red
Tears began to flow from the mother's eyes as she heard her son's words
Very happy to know her son's kindness, she hugged him tightly
Performance of duty should not be abandoned
Author: Dr. Haripal Dwivedi
The festival was a very old banyan tree
The branches of that banyan tree were spread out everywhere
There was a beautiful large lake on one side of the tree
On the other side was the cemetery
Young men and women were bathing in the lake
The children were playing there
The joys and pleasures of the people were carried out on the banks of the lake
The tree was watching all this
There was indeed a cemetery on the other side
There was cremation, crying for relatives and so on
The tree always watched this scene too
Once a traveler sat down under that tree to rest
He saw the view of the lake and the view of the cemetery
When he saw both, he started thinking
Is this world beautiful or terrible
Is it right to enjoy yourself here or to escape?
Is there nectar or poison here?
Is the world happy or painful?
Thinking like this, he became agitated
Anxiously he wandered around the tree
He saw satisfying views on the shore of the lake
But all the scenes in the cemetery are sad
So then what kind of reality is this world?
He thought about it again
Meanwhile some fruits fell from the tree
The traveler took them and ate them
His stomach is full
He was satisfied
But his doubts have not disappeared
Who is here to answer my doubts
Thinking this the traveler looked everywhere
The spirit of the old banyan tree had been watching the anxiety of the traveler for a long time
he said to the traveler in a comforting voice
O traveler, there is continuity in the world of creation and rhythm
The same is true of happiness and sorrow
What is the point of getting anxious when you see pleasure and pain?
Look at me I see pleasant and painful scenes every moment
But I do my duty quietly
It is my duty to give shade and fruit
Attached to my duty, I am not disturbed by external appearances
But I must never give up my duty
Now the traveler had gained true knowledge
External pleasure and pain should be seen with equality
But the performance of duty should never be abandoned
The traveler realized this
He bowed to the banyan tree with reverence and followed his own path
The devotee is the head of the family
Harinarayan: Kerala
Kulasekara, king of the kingdom of Chera, was very devout to God
He was devoted to listening to the story of Hari every day
He would bring any scholar to his palace to tell the story of Hari
